    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>June 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you very sincerely for your kindness in having sent me your Experimental Researches &amp;c &amp;c.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> The subject is one which much interests me, &amp; as soon as I have finished reading a book in hand, I will assuredly begin with interest in yours—</p>
<p>— I remain | Dear Sir | Yours faithfully &amp; obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C. H. Blackley, 7 July 1873</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s annotated copy of <hi rend="italic">Experimental researches on the causes and nature of catarrhus æstivus (hay-fever or hay-asthma)</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_670.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Blackley 1873</ref>) is in the Darwin Library–CUL (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi></ref> 1: 59).</note>
        </div>        
            
